  "local_port": 47602,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why is the corner of my eye soring?",
  "response": "There are several possible reasons why the corner of your eye might be sore. Here are some common causes:\n\n### 1. **Eye Strain**\n   - Prolonged use of screens, reading, or focusing on close-up tasks can cause eye strain, leading to discomfort in the corner of your eye.\n\n### 2. **Dry Eye Syndrome**\n   - Insufficient tear production or poor tear quality can cause dryness and irritation, often felt in the inner or outer corners of the eye.\n\n### 3. **Conjunctivitis (Pink Eye)**\n   - An infection or inflammation of the conjunctiva (the clear membrane covering the white part of the eye) can cause redness, itching, and soreness, including in the corners of the eye.\n\n### 4. **Blepharitis**\n   - Inflammation of the eyelid margins, often due to bacterial overgrowth or skin conditions like dandruff, can cause soreness and irritation in the corners of the eye.\n\n### 5. **Stye or Chalazion**\n   - A stye (infected oil gland) or chalazion (blocked oil gland) near the corner of the eye can cause localized soreness, swelling, and tenderness.\n\n### 6. **Foreign Body**\n   - A small particle, like dust or an eyelash, trapped in the corner of your eye can cause irritation and soreness.\n\n### 7. **Allergies**\n   - Seasonal or environmental allergens (e.g., pollen, dust, pet dander) can cause itching, redness, and soreness in the eyes, including the corners.\n\n### 8. **Blocked Tear Duct**\n   - If your tear duct is blocked, it can cause pain, swelling, and irritation in the inner corner of the eye, along with excessive tearing or discharge.\n\n### 9. **Eye Infections**\n   - Bacterial or viral infections, such as keratitis or dacryocystitis (infection of the tear sac), can cause soreness and discomfort.\n\n### 10. **Trauma or Injury**\n   - Rubbing your eyes too hard, accidental scratches, or other trauma can cause soreness in the corner of the eye.\n\n### What to Do:\n- **Rest Your Eyes:** Take breaks from screens and reduce eye strain.\n- **Artificial Tears:** Use lubricating eye drops to relieve dryness.\n- **Warm Compress:** Apply a warm compress to reduce inflammation and ease discomfort.\n- **Avoid Rubbing:** This can worsen irritation or introduce bacteria.\n- **Check for Allergens:** Avoid triggers and consider antihistamine eye drops if allergies are the cause.\n\nIf the soreness persists, worsens, or is accompanied by vision changes, discharge, or severe pain, see an eye doctor (optometrist or ophthalmologist) for a proper evaluation and treatment.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
